[2] UK (England)
Date: Fri 4 Oct 2013
Source: Health Protection Report, Volume 7 Number 40 [summ., edited]
http://www.hpa.org.uk/hpr/news/default.htm#msls


Measles cases in England up to the end of August [2013]
-------------------------------------------------------
For the 4th successive month the number of laboratory confirmed cases of measles in England has declined, with only 21 cases confirmed in August [2013], bringing the number reported since the start of the year to 1386 cases. In August, South-West region reported the most cases (8), almost all of which were associated with an on-going outbreak in the area of a new D8 strain, MVs/Bristol.GBR/21.13. There was a smaller cluster of cases in Yorkshire and Humber region of a B3 strain, MVs/Bradford.GBR/26.13. Sporadic cases of MVs/Taunton.GBR/27.12 continue to be identified.

So far this year, 274 (20 percent) cases have been associated with primary and secondary school outbreaks. Small outbreaks have also been reported from "hard-to-reach" populations with known low vaccine coverage such as the travelling community [Roma] and the ultra-Orthodox Jewish community in north London [see ProMED-mail measles update 39]. Overall 294 (21 percent) of all cases in 2013 were admitted to hospital; 46 reported complications including pneumonia, meningitis and gastroenteritis.

As previously reported, the shift towards cases in secondary school age groups during 2013 is likely to be due to the fall in routine vaccine coverage of MMR between 1999 and 2005. To reduce the risk of larger outbreaks of measles in the next academic year, Public Health England, the Department of Health and NHS England announced an MMR catch-up programme in late April. The campaign has targeted children aged between 10 and 16 years who have a record of none or incomplete MMR vaccination. Returns from the NHS Areas Teams confirm that almost 5000 practices have already signed up to participate in the programme. The service involves sending letters from general practices inviting under-vaccinated children to attend the surgery for vaccination. The primary target population was the estimated 8 percent of that age group who had received no vaccine (around 1/3rd of a million). Secondary targets included a similar number of that age group who had received one dose of MMR, and a similar number of children in other age groups.

Data has been extracted from approximately 4400 practices (around half of the total) on the MMR status of children turning 10 to 16 years of age in August 2013. Comparing this with children aged 9-15 years in 2012, it suggests that the proportion recorded as unvaccinated fell by around 1.8 percent (representing around 42 500 children in the participating practices). If this progress was replicated nationally this suggests that around 78 000 unvaccinated children have received MMR since last year [2012]. The proportion recorded as having received 2 doses of MMR has increased by 2.5 percent. Although some of this may represent data cleaning, this scale of increase is consistent with the vaccine ordering data, which suggests that around 200 000 extra doses have been used. So far, most vaccination has been conducted in primary care, although schools campaigns were conducted in response to local outbreaks in many areas during the last academic year. Plans are being developed to sustain these activities and to undertake specific programmes in some schools during the next 2 terms.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is clear from the initial statement that: "For the 4th successive month the number of laboratory confirmed cases of measles in England has declined, with only 21 cases confirmed in August, bringing the number reported since the start of the year to 1386 cases" -- the 2013 measles outbreak in England (and probably the remainder of the United Kingdom) has passed its peak and is unlikely to recur to the same extent.

The relevance for future outbreaks of the persistence of more than a single genotype of measles virus is unclear at present. - Mod.CP

