******
[5] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Thu 3 Oct 2013
Source: Sunshine Coast Daily [summ., edited]
http://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/its-time-to-get-the-jab-adults-urged-to-take-advan/2037964/


9th case of measles confirmed in Ipswich
----------------------------------------
Health officials expect more cases to be confirmed before the outbreak ends. A total of 8 of the 9 confirmed cases have been in adults, with one baby also suffering the disease. West Moreton Hospital and Health Service public health physician Dr Heidi Carroll said any adult with 2 doses of the Measles Mumps Rubella [vaccine] is 99 per cent immune.

Dr Carroll said a higher vaccination rate amongst adults would help prevent the outbreak spreading. "Adults who were born in 1966 or later and who do not have documentation of having received measles vaccine, or having had the infection, are particularly at risk of contracting the disease, in the current outbreak setting." Dr Carroll said it was unlikely the measles outbreak could become wide-spread. According to West Moreton-Oxley Medicare local, 94.45 per cent of children under the age of 5 have been vaccinated. Measles symptoms usually start around 10 days after infection. But symptoms can occur between 7 and 18 days after infection.

Health Minister Lawrence Springborg said with the eradication of so many diseases in the past generation, some parts of the community have forgotten how serious those diseases are. He said parents who don't vaccinate their children put the health of their own children and others at risk. Children can receive the measles vaccination from 12 months [of age].

The 1st measles case was confirmed by health officials on 6 Sep 2013; 2 weeks later 4 cases had been confirmed, with the 8th and 9th detected this week [week of 30 Sep 2013]. The symptoms of measles are usually treated with rest, plenty of fluids, and paracetamol.

